description:
From Middle English twelfthe, twelfte, from Old English twelfta (“twelfth”), from Proto-Germanic *twaliftô (“twelfth”), equivalent to twelve +‎ -th. Cognate with Scots twelft (“twelfth”), Saterland Frisian tweelfte (“twelfth”), West Frisian tolfde (“twelfth”), Dutch twaalfde (“twelfth”), German Low German twalfde, twalvde (“twelfth”), German zwölfte (“twelfth”), Danish tolvte (“twelfth”),
Swedish tolfte (“twelfth”), Icelandic tólfta (“twelfth”).

entries.meaning: The ordinal form of the number twelve, describing a person or thing in position number 12 of a sequence.
examples: The answer appears on the twelfth page of the book.
She finished twelfth in the race.

entries.meaning: One of twelve equal parts of a whole.
examples: Five twelfths of the population voted in support of the proposal.

entries.meaning: (music) An interval equal to an octave plus a fifth.
